Both species are found under rocks, logs and leaves, and in the ground of damp wooded forests (Dillon and Dillon, 1961; Jaeger, 1980). 
Both species forage nocturnally in the leaf litter for similar invertebrate prey and retreat to moist cover objects as the forest floor dries (Dillon and Dillon, 1961; Jaeger, 1980).
Resident salamanders were significantly more aggressive toward other salamanders (P 5 0.0004) and beetles (P 5 0.023)

% Hickerson2012Interactionsforestfloor
In salamander removal plots spider abundance increased by 34\%, and carabid beetles decreased by 15\% relative to the control.
Interaction strengths were strongest in the drier summer months when territorial predators were confined in spatially fixed microhabitats.
a growing body of evidence suggests that terrestrial salamanders in the family Plethodontidae are important regulators of invertebrate communities and of decomposition of organic material on temperate forestfloors (Burton and Likens, 1975; Hairston, 1987; Wyman, 1998; Rooney et al., 2000; Walton, 2005; Walton and Steckler, 2005).
but the diet of P. cinereus is well documented (Jaeger, 1990; Maglia, 1996; Adams and Rohlf, 2000; Anthony et al., 2008)
Although previous studies suggest that the relationships between Plethodon cinereus and large arthropod predators is competitive (Gall et al., 2003; Hickerson et al., 2004; Anthony et al., 2007; Figura, 2007) 
rather than predatory, the ways in which the interactions function within the intricate forest-floor food web are unclear.
Therefore, microhabitats under rocks and logs become refugia from desiccation for terrestrial amphibians and many arthropods (Jaeger, 1980b)
Conversely, beetles (open circles) were negatively affected by centipedes but positively affected by salamanders. 
The removal of salamanders had no significant effect on carabid beetle abundance (P 5 0.295, F 5 9.08), but there was a significant increase in carabid beetles in the centipede removal treatment (P , 0.0001, F 5 9.08, mean 5 1.35/plot) compared to controls (mean 5 0.915/plot, Fig. 2d).
Salamanders had significant negative effects on spiders (sign test, P , 0.0001, z 5 25.67) and significant positive effects on beetles (sign test, P 5 0.019, z 5 2.33).
Effects of salamanders on both beetles and on spiders were most evident in the summer months (Fig. 3b).
The existing evidence on beetle – salamander interactions indicates that the salamander, Plethodon cinereus, and the carabid beetle, Platynus tenuicollis, are mutually territorial (Gall et al., 2003); 
and, therefore, it is unlikely that salamanders and carabid beetles would be positively associated with each other.
We found that, in summer, interaction strengths between salamanders and IG predators were of greater magnitude than in the spring and fall (Fig. 3b, points farthest from the zero line) 
suggesting that competitive effects are strongest when salamanders are confined to microhabitat beneath cover objects. 
During wetter periods, in the spring and fall, when salamanders forage widely in the complex microhabitat of the surrounding leaf litter and vegetation, their role may be more like that described by Rooney et al. (2006) 
where predators regulate prey in fast chains before moving from those depleted chains to the chains that have experienced some degree of recovery.


Effet obtenue:
Notre schémas basé sur un effet top down n'a montré aucun effet des prédateurs sur les proies.
Il n'y a pas eu de différence significative dans la probabilité d'occupation des carabes de petite taille par apport a la probabilité d'occupation des salamandres.
Aussi, la probabiltié d'occupation des salamandre et des deux groupe de carabes n'a pas eu d'effet significatif sur la la biomasse des collemboles.

Les coupes forestières ne semble donc pas avoir d'effet indirectes sur la probabiltié d'occupation des petite carabes et la biomasse des collemboles dans notre études.


